subject: wasm: ensure cursor reverts after window resize

messages.message:
Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The behavior doesn't seem correct. After releasing the mouse button after a resize, the cursor reverts to system default, even if it is kept still inside the resize region. On macOS and Windows, the behavior is that the cursor only changes to system default once it actually leaves the resize region.

The bug report and patch subject is also misleading. The bug is that the cursor does not revert to default when leaving a resize region. It doesn't seem related to the actual resizing at all. I think the better solution is to detect when the cursor has moved from a resize region to a non-resize region and just call changeCursor normally in that case.

Additonally, it seems very hacky to store a pointer to the last window in the cursor. The documentation in QPlatformCursor states that setOverrideCursor can be implemented where the cursor is a property of the application or the screen, it seems its usage is more tied to implementing cursors in a windowless environment. There is a reason it doesn't pass a QWindow cursor, after all.

I think a simpler and more conceptually correct solution could be detecting when cursor has moved from resize region to non-resize region and just call changeCursor normally.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

In the case where the cursor is moved from one resize area to another then outside the resize area, it will be stuck as the cursor in the first resize area. I think this is because of the overriden cursor logic. Doesn't the window or environment have a default cursor it can revert to if moves out of a resize area?

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1
> 
> In the case where the cursor is moved from one resize area to another then outside the resize area, it will be stuck as the cursor in the first resize area. I think this is because of the overriden cursor logic. Doesn't the window or environment have a default cursor it can revert to if moves out of a resize area?

I think it would be best to override the the cursor on the wasm platform plugin level, i,e. don't call QWindow::setCursor(). This way we leave any application-set cursor as-is, and don't have to keep track of which QWindow to restore the cursor on.

This matches Qt on macOS behavior at least: QWindow::cursor() keeps returning ArrowCursor, also when the WS has changed the cursor to the resize cursor.

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> > Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1
> > 
> > In the case where the cursor is moved from one resize area to another then outside the resize area, it will be stuck as the cursor in the first resize area. I think this is because of the overriden cursor logic. Doesn't the window or environment have a default cursor it can revert to if moves out of a resize area?
> 
> I think it would be best to override the the cursor on the wasm platform plugin level, i,e. don't call QWindow::setCursor(). This way we leave any application-set cursor as-is, and don't have to keep track of which QWindow to restore the cursor on.
> 
> This matches Qt on macOS behavior at least: QWindow::cursor() keeps returning ArrowCursor, also when the WS has changed the cursor to the resize cursor.

oohh... tricky! (just tested this) This also happens on windows. At least for Qt apps. Is this the native platform behavior as well?

When resizing, the widget and window ->cursor().shape(); calls can change to Qt::IBeamCursor, but the visual cursor is still the resizey one. 

Seems like crazy wrong behavior to me, but whatever. :)

Patch Set 1:

Working theory: the unconditional reserve() ensured that we detach()ed before the call to data(). If, after this change, we now check a shared string with excess capacity(), we don't call reserve(), so we detach() only in data(), in which capacity() will revert back to size(), and we're scribbling off the end of the buffer.

Testing a fix as we^WI speak.

Patch Set 3:

If we are talking only about the shuffled keys case, than when we don't reserve() I observe:
- insertion is always better in Qt 6
- reading is better in Qt 5
- removal is better in Qt 6 up to about 2M items, and Qt 5 is better above this number
When we do reserve(), I observe:
- insertion is better in Qt 6 up to about 4M items, and Qt 5 is better above this number
- reading is better in Qt 5 (it doesn't depend on reserve() being called or not)
- removal is better in Qt 6 up to about 2M items, and Qt 5 is better above this number

Done using new test attached to QTBUG-91739 today.

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> If we are talking only about the shuffled keys case, than when we don't reserve() I observe:
> - insertion is always better in Qt 6
> - reading is better in Qt 5

> When we do reserve(), I observe:

> - reading is better in Qt 5 (it doesn't depend on reserve() being called or not)
> - removal is better in Qt 6 up to about 2M items, and Qt 5 is better above this number
> 
> Done using new test attached to QTBUG-91739 today.

I wondered why I always got 0ms for reading independent of the size of the table. Turns out your test case has a bug, in that you're not using the return value from the reads. So the compiler managed (at least for me) to completely optimise the whole read loop away. Please change the code to use temp += hash.value(...) and do something with the final value after reading (e.g. print it). Otherwise the reading results will be wrong.

Just ran your test as well (after modifying the reading code). Reading is faster in Qt6 up to ~2M elements (e.g. 13ms in Qt 6 vs 22ms in Qt 5 for 1M elements). 

One can also see that QHash in Qt6 is consistent (independent of how keys are ordered), something we didn't have in Qt 5. Calculating the hash value is of course slower in Qt 6 because of that (it was a no-op for integers in Qt 5). We know that this hashing was bad for esp. pointers in Qt 5, but could also have easily caused problems in other cases.

It would be good to figure out why reading doesn't scale as well as it should for very large hash tables. I'll try to do some more investigations, but would propose that we merge what we have here in the meantime.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

The following warnings cannot be ported

- settingsFile() => that logic is only part of the qmllint tool and not the library and it's better that way
- testUnqualified() => we insist on actually checking not only the line and column of the error message but also the text that we underline as context. as long as we want to do that it's easier to just leave this using the tool where we can just grep through the output.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Having a few remaining tests directly invoking the tool (instead of only relying on the library) has the added benefit of acting as an integration (vs unit) test, so I think that's fine, given that we now only rarely spawn a new process.

Patch Set 10:

I don't think we should ever swap from the system default. If the user wishes to use something that is not the default, they can explicitly choose that by at least three ways.

That reminds me to finish the -fsingle-global-definition code (https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/355956, original https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/21156). I think GCC with support for it hasn't been released yet, it's GCC 12, but Clang might have.

Patch Set 10:

> I don't think we should ever swap from the system default. If the user wishes to use something that is not the default, they can explicitly choose that by at least three ways.

I'm not sure I follow.

The default is not changed, neither for building Qt, nor user projects.

But Qt builders can opt into building Qt with mold via -DINPUT_linker=mold.

That Qt can then be used by users on another machine with system ld, it won't use mold by default.

Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1

> I'm not sure I follow.
> 
> The default is not changed, neither for building Qt, nor user projects.
> 
> But Qt builders can opt into building Qt with mold via -DINPUT_linker=mold.

That's how it should be. I just meant that we shouldn't automatically choose it.

In any case, this isn't needed because there are two other ways of doing so. People can simply set the CMAKE_CXX_LINKER_FLAGS.

Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

After a longer discussion with Thiago on IRC:

I think we should go for this as it restores QDS compatibility with Qt 5 (something we promise).

There's a side effect to QSettings, where we also restore compatibility, but will now use the typedef'ed name when writing variants (as QSettings forces the QDS version to 4.0). I think we should (for 6.3) fix this by using a different tag in QSettings (e.g. @QVariant instead of @Variant) that properly streams our a the variant including the version of the QDS we're using. Might mean that we need to add a compatibility mode to QSettings if people really need the old format.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

Can you say what the advantage is of doing it like this?

Playing devil's advocate here, I'd mention that our tests already are slow enough :) I get that the huge magic number is hard to come up with in the first place (though maybe it could be calculated at runtime instead?), but what's the point in throwing CPU time at the problem instead of keeping the manually-found configuration?

Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

> Can you say what the advantage is of doing it like this?

Not having to manually update the seed and keys to something that works when there are internal changes.

> Playing devil's advocate here, I'd mention that our tests already are slow enough :) I get that the huge magic number is hard to come up with in the first place (though maybe it could be calculated at runtime instead?), but what's the point in throwing CPU time at the problem instead of keeping the manually-found configuration?

Well, the configuration changes in the next patch in the series, so I added this to avoid having to update the values (and getting an error if something changes and the test no longer works as expected).

Patch Set 1:

> Well, the configuration changes in the next patch in the series, so I added this to avoid having to update the values (and getting an error if something changes and the test no longer works as expected).

Patch Set 5:

Ossi, this is making progress, but it's clear that - with the current speed - we're still months (if not years) away from a fully approved translation of all messages.

I'm therefore leaning towards merging this and the parent commit as soon as it's approved, and merge the rest of the translations iteratively once they are ready. This is not what you originally proposed. Anyhow, also a partical update of the translation would be an improvement over the current stale one. 

Do you have strong rejections against this approach?

Patch Set 5:

> Do you have strong rejections against this approach?

of course i do.
if there is no other realistic option, we can merge this piece-wise, but i'm not going to approve pieces which are known bad.

Patch Set 5:

> [...]
> if there is no other realistic option, we can merge this piece-wise, but i'm not going to approve pieces which are known bad.

THat's clear, and I didn't want to suggest anything else. I was just suggesting merging single commits of this series _after_ they are approved.

Patch Set 8:

ok. now the problem is that this cannot be integrated without integrating the template update, and doing that as-is would be against my policy. so what needs to be done is to squash it onto the template update, then soft-reset that new commit, and re-commit it selectively (with git gui) with the change-id of this change here. the squashed commit itself can also be pushed, so it would be easier to rebase the other changes later.

the alternative would be to push it all as-is to a temporary branch, which would be squash-merged later. that would be the easy way to "get it out of the way", but obviously users couldn't use the translations yet (well, this is a dead branch by now anyway, so whatever).

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> ok. now the problem is that this cannot be integrated without integrating the template update, and doing that as-is would be against my policy. so what needs to be done is to squash it onto the template update, then soft-reset that new commit, and re-commit it selectively (with git gui) with the change-id of this change here. the squashed commit itself can also be pushed, so it would be easier to rebase the other changes later.

That's ... a whole lot of tedious work, for little gain IMO. Not sure when I find the time to do this.

Can't we just squash this with the update? What harm does that cause?

Patch Set 8:

> Can't we just squash this with the update?

oh, you totally can. then do the same with all the other partial changes, and finally strip the line number info, before actually integrating the whole thing.
but somehow i have the suspicion that this is not what you have in mind ...

> What harm does that cause?

you mean, other than bloating the repo and making the diffs completely unreadable? nothing.

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> > Can't we just squash this with the update?
> 
> oh, you totally can. then do the same with all the other partial changes, and finally strip the line number info, before actually integrating the whole thing.

What line number info? The current patches do not feature file/line information.

> but somehow i have the suspicion that this is not what you have in mind ...
> 
> > What harm does that cause?
> 
> you mean, other than bloating the repo and making the diffs completely unreadable? nothing.

Well, even if the diff is big, it's just text. So every single .png we don't check in or update saves more.

Patch Set 8:

> What line number info? The current patches do not feature file/line information.

oh, indeed, that makes the argument moot.
(come to think of it, this omission actually makes sense - non-technical translators don't have the qt source code available anyway, so unless they use the reference to look up the source on the web, it's useless info anyway.)

> Well, even if the diff is big, it's just text. So every single .png we don't check in or update saves more.

i think that's actually rarely going to be the case. text compresses much better than png (in part because pngs are already compressed), but it's *a lot* of text.
it's still not that much in total numbers, but that repo is lean and mean so far, which makes it pleasant to work with.

regardless of size, i still don't like bulk-updating the template, because realistically it will mean that most of the source strings are updated pointlessly and thus just add noise - if that wasn't going to be the case, then we wouldn't be having this discussion, as we'd have merged a single commit a long time ago. also, the ping-pong with the message statuses is inherently noise (even if it compresses to almost nothing).

so all in all i don't think that's a very good process. we'd be much better off using different tooling for the review (transifex was on the table, but it's kinda broken, and after several months they still didn't care to fix the underlying issues - going to crowdin or weblate instead seems more realistic at this point).

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> > What line number info? The current patches do not feature file/line information.
> 
> oh, indeed, that makes the argument moot.
> (come to think of it, this omission actually makes sense - non-technical translators don't have the qt source code available anyway, so unless they use the reference to look up the source on the web, it's useless info anyway.)
> 
> > Well, even if the diff is big, it's just text. So every single .png we don't check in or update saves more.
> 
> i think that's actually rarely going to be the case. text compresses much better than png (in part because pngs are already compressed), but it's *a lot* of text.
> it's still not that much in total numbers, but that repo is lean and mean so far, which makes it pleasant to work with.
> 
> regardless of size, i still don't like bulk-updating the template, because realistically it will mean that most of the source strings are updated pointlessly and thus just add noise - if that wasn't going to be the case, then we wouldn't be having this discussion, as we'd have merged a single commit a long time ago. also, the ping-pong with the message statuses is inherently noise (even if it compresses to almost nothing).
> 
> so all in all i don't think that's a very good process. we'd be much better off using different tooling for the review (transifex was on the table, but it's kinda broken, and after several months they still didn't care to fix the underlying issues - going to crowdin or weblate instead seems more realistic at this point).

I think I get your reservations, but creating a new commit with "just" the parts of the parent commit merged is a hell to do on command line. I tried it, and gave up after 1.5 hours.

So unless someone else has better git foo and picks it up, I'm afraid we're blocked here.

Patch Set 8:

To me, if the translations are correct then we should accept them, I get that we could potentially do this better in a single commit or something. But aside from that, since the strings in this case are seen as being correct then we should just go ahead and merge them already.

Does it need to be moved first or will it merge upwards in this case for Qt Creator?

Patch Set 8:

one thing you seem to be missing is that for translations, looks *do* matter. it's better to have no translation at all than one that is gravely incomplete. that's why the build files (at least the qmake ones) contain code to disable translations that are below 95% complete, though i never actually pulled it off on release. but the wider point here is that a translation that is trickling in at the rate this one does is just utterly pointless, because it's slower than the source strings change.

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> one thing you seem to be missing is that for translations, looks *do* matter. it's better to have no translation at all than one that is gravely incomplete. that's why the build files (at least the qmake ones) contain code to disable translations that are below 95% complete, though i never actually pulled it off on release. but the wider point here is that a translation that is trickling in at the rate this one does is just utterly pointless, because it's slower than the source strings change.

Respectfully I disagree, because if someone else picks it up then they have less work to do, otherwise there is the risk of overlapping work and commercial users can also save time by having their translators do what is missing.

Though I appreciate your point, but we run the risk of losing the efforts already done by someone here, because Qt Creator is changing quickly so there is a risk of losing this work already done. Maybe we could get this in so it is easier for someone to pick up the rest and do it in one.

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> one thing you seem to be missing is that for translations, looks *do* matter. it's better to have no translation at all than one that is gravely incomplete. that's why the build files (at least the qmake ones) contain code to disable translations that are below 95% complete, though i never actually pulled it off on release. but the wider point here is that a translation that is trickling in at the rate this one does is just utterly pointless, because it's slower than the source strings change.

I think that's subjective, and IMNSHO ideally should be the user's decision in the end.

In any case, we have a few translated strings here that seem good, which took work to create, and I think we should integrate as much as possible as step forward to a perfect world.

Whether we actually use a highly incomplete translation in the end is pretty much an independent decision that can be made e.g in two lines of code in a separate patch, and this can be done when the time is there, not in advance, before doing the first incremental step.

Patch Set 8:

re usefulness of partial translations: we don't have a real story for those who don't read english anyway. that leaves us with users who'd use a translation for familiarity or aesthetic reasons ... for whom the mish-mash presented by qtc wouldn't be really appealing. 

i can theoretically buy the "basis for commercial translations" argument, but then, if anyone really cared, i'd expect more contributions, or at least complaints. i figure there is a reason for tqtc management's proven track record of not giving a flyin' hoot about translations. 😉

the risk of duplicated work exists only for those future translators who go against common sense AND the explicitly written down advice to coordinate the work with us. which is admittedly remarkably common.

anyway kai, what problem did you run into? i'd expect that it would be fairly efficient to split the squashed (template update) + (partial translation) commit the same way as the broken down series was produced in the first place. unfortunately, you never answered my question on https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt-creator/qt-creator/+/338053 how you did that.

Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

Looks good in my opinion!
The only things I don't like is how the "reject" button in the button box is unnaturally large for the Basic and Universal styles. But I am not sure why this is happening.

Also, the FolderDialogPage.qml file in the manual test project should also be updated (in my opinion) to use the word "folder" rather than "file" for id's, and strings. (and maybe move the acceptLabel and rejectLabel properties next to each other)

Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)

> Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1
> 
> (1 comment)
> 
> Looks good in my opinion!
> The only things I don't like is how the "reject" button in the button box is unnaturally large for the Basic and Universal styles. But I am not sure why this is happening.

For me, OK is very narrow and Cancel is half the width of the dialog.  Maybe the same reason as why the text fields are too small in the dialogs page in the example, which actually is pretty typical for Universal.  I'm pretty sure I reported a bug about it once, can't find it now though.  I posted screenshots on QTBUG-87798.

I already mentioned that ShowDirsOnly doesn't make sense here, but that can be another patch I guess?

There's something weird with selectedFolder but that's probably in C++, not the style.  Press the up arrow in the dialog several times, and watch how selectedFolder gets out of sync with the actual directory you are looking at.  It seems to choose a subdirectory of the selection instead of the selection itself.

But otherwise the styling itself looks ok I think.

Thanks, fixed.
